introduction.p:
A Sylow p-subgroupSubgroupSylowp-subgroupSylow p-subgroup P of a group G is a maximal p-subgroup of G. To prove the other two Sylow Theorems, we need to consider conjugate subgroups as opposed to conjugate elements in a group. For a group G, let {\mathcal S} be the collection of all subgroups of G. For any subgroup H, {\mathcal S} is a H-set, where H acts on {\mathcal S} by conjugation. That is, we have an action
H \times {\mathcal S} \rightarrow {\mathcal S}
defined by
h \cdot K \mapsto hKh^{-1}
for K in {\mathcal S}.

sage.input:
def all_sylow(G, p):
    '''Form the set of all distinct Sylow p-subgroups of G'''
    scriptP = []
    P = G.sylow_subgroup(p)
    for x in G:
        H = P.conjugate(x)
        if not(H in scriptP):
            scriptP.append(H)
    return scriptP
